Polyketides synthases (PKS) catalyze  repeated condensation of acetyl coenzyme A via malonyl-CoA. Type II  PKSs produce aromatic polyketides, and are composed of separate mono  and  bi-functional  enzymes  that  interact  during  biosynthesis  [3]. Moraes).   journal homepage: www.elsevier.com/locate/bbagen  Background:  The  N-terminal  domain  of  Tetracenomycin  aromatase/cyclase  (TcmN),  an  enzyme  derived  from  Streptomyces  glaucescens,  is  involved  in  polyketide  cyclization,  aromatization,  and  folding.  Polyketides  are  a  diverse class of secondary metabolites produced by certain groups of bacteria, fungi, and plants with various  pharmaceutical applications. Examples include antibiotics, such as tetracycline, and anticancer drugs, such as  doxorubicin.  Because  TcmN  is  a  promising  enzyme  for  in  vitro  production  of  polyketides,  it  is  important  to  identify conditions that enhance its thermal resistance and optimize its function.  Methods:  TcmN  unfolding,  stability,  and  dynamics  were  evaluated  by  fluorescence  spectroscopy,  circular  di- chroism, nuclear magnetic resonance  15N relaxation experiments, and microsecond molecular dynamics (MD)  simulations.  Results: TcmN thermal resistance was enhanced at low protein and high salt concentrations, was pH-dependent,  and denaturation was irreversible. Conformational dynamics on the μs-ms timescale were detected for residues in  the substrate-binding cavity, and two predominant conformers representing opened and closed cavity states were  observed in the MD simulations.  Conclusion: Based on the results, a mechanism was proposed in which the thermodynamics and kinetics of the  TcmN  conformational  equilibrium  modulate  enzyme  function  by  favoring  ligand  binding  and  avoiding  aggregation.  General significance: Understanding the principles underlying TcmN stability and dynamics may help in designing  mutants with optimal properties for biotechnological applications. cyclase, TcmN, is directly involved in the cyclization, aromatization, and  folding of polyketides [4]. In vivo and in vitro, TcmN catalyzes the first  (C9-C14)  and  second  (C7-C16)  ring  formations  [5,6].  The  minimal  functional  composition  of  type  II  PKSs  is  known  as  minimal  PKS  (MinPKS) and is composed of a ketosynthase, a chain length factor, an  acyl  carrier  protein  (ACP),  and  a  malonyl  transferase.  The  MinPKS  produces a highly reactive linear poly-β-keto intermediate, and specific  components of type II PKS promote its correct aromatization and folding  (Fig. 1). In a non-reducing system, the growing poly-β-ketone interme- diate  is  transported  directly  from  the  ketosynthase  to  the  aromatase/  V.S. Structurally, TcmN is a Bet v 1-like superfamily protein (Fig. S1), like  the lipid/sterol-binding StAR-related lipid transfer (START) proteins [9]  and PR-10 family of plant pathogenesis-related proteins [10,11]. Bet v 1-  like superfamily proteins have diverse biological functions, and typically  bear  low  primary  sequence  identity.  For  instance,  TcmN  shares  14%  identity with Bet v 1, from Betula verrucose. Bet v 1-like proteins can bind  several  molecules,  such  as  flavonoids,  steroids,  hormones,  and  lipids  [11,12], and have the common characteristic of undergoing significant  conformational changes to carry out their functions [4,13,14].  TcmN  possesses  a  β-sandwich  fold  consisting  of  a  seven-stranded  antiparallel β-sheet, a long C-terminal α-helix that runs down the cen- ter of the β-sandwich, and two small helices between β1 and β2, forming  a  helix–loop–helix  motif  that  seals  one  end  of  the  β-sandwich  [4]  (Fig. 1). TcmN has a ~ 20 Å deep interior pocket with a distribution of  hydrophobic and polar residues that can accommodate an ACP-bound  decaketide (20 carbons) (Fig. 1). The cavity has a narrow neck defined  by residues W65, F88, L129, Y35, T132, T133, E34, and R82 (Fig. 1).  S67 and R82 anchor the polyketide, and the size and shape of the cavity  modulates chain folding for C9-C14 first-ring cyclization (Fig. 1). C9-  C14 first-ring cyclization and interactions with residues in the narrow  neck region orient C7 and C16 so that C7 carbonyl hydrogen bonds with  R82. The C16 methylene is positioned near E34 and Y35, favoring C7-

C16  second-ring cyclization (Fig.  1). The TcmN cavity can accommo- date up to three linearly fused rings, and the third ring cyclization likely  happens spontaneously (Fig. 1). During the biosynthesis of the anthra- cycline antibiotic Tetracenomycin C, the fourth ring formation is cata- lyzed by another enzyme, TcmI [15,16].  Conformational changes are important for substrate binding events.  The sampling of opened states is likely needed for substrate binding to  TcmN [11], and may also be critical for enzyme activity since the TcmN  cavity is composed of several hydrophobic residues that could trigger  aggregation  when  exposed  to  solvent.  A  fine-tuned  conformational  equilibrium  might  exist  to  allow  ligand  binding  and  to  avoid  TcmN  aggregation.  Because  the  thermodynamics,  kinetics,  and  interactions  involved in TcmN opening and closing are not well understood, identi- fying  conditions  that  favor  TcmN  stability  and  function,  and  under- standing  how  ARO/CYCs evolved  to  solve  the  puzzle  of  “function  vs.  aggregation” are important steps toward it's possible application for in  vitro polyketide production.  In the present study, the role of conformational dynamics in TcmN  function  and  aggregation  was  investigated.  Based  on  the  results,  a  mechanism  was  proposed  in  which  the  accessibility  of  the  TcmN  hy- drophobic cavity is regulated by a dynamic equilibrium between open  and closed states. Our findings present a crucial step for understanding  TcmN function, and provide useful information for TcmN engineering  for biotechnological applications.  V.S. Valadares et al.

Maintaining  protein  stability  is  essential  in  biochemical  and  biotechnological  processes.  To  assess  and  compare  TcmN  thermal  resistance under different conditions and evaluate its folding, CD and  fluorescence  spectroscopy  measurements  were  performed  at  different  temperatures, pH, and salt concentrations. The CD spectra indicate that  TcmN unfolded at temperatures between 40 and 55  C (Fig. 2). TcmN  unfolding was irreversible and followed by aggregation, as seen in the  CD spectrum acquired at 20  C and  90  C (Fig. S2A and 2A).  Thermal denaturation is also irreversible for Bet v 1 [42] and (S)-NCS  [43], both Bet v 1-like family members. The irreversible denaturation  process may be related to the central cavity's high hydrophobicity, and  the  tendency  to  aggregate  when  hydrophobic  residues  are  exposed  during unfolding. ThT binding assays were performed to assess if TcmN  aggregates  have  amyloid  properties.  For  comparison,  p53  DBD  was  included  as  a  positive  control  [44].  TcmN  did  not  yield  ThT  fluores- cence, indicating that it does not form ordered aggregates (Fig. 2).  TcmN  thermal  resistance  was  pH-dependent.  CD  spectra  taken  at  different pH values indicate that TcmN retained its secondary structure  at pH 8.1 (blue line) and 6.8 (red line), but exhibited a small change in  intensity around 210 nm at pH 5.6 (black line), indicating partial loss of  secondary structure at lower pH (Fig. S2B and C). Salt concentration also  may modulate TcmN stability, with higher NaCl and NaI concentrations  leading to enhanced thermal stability (Fig. S2D).

TcmN thermal stability was also concentration-dependent, decaying  as protein concentration increased (Fig. 2C and S3). TcmN was ~4  C  more  resistant  to  temperature  unfolding  at  60  μM  than  at  125  μM  (Fig. S2E-F). Thermal unfolding can be used to describe thermodynamic  stability using the Gibbs free energy difference between the folded and  the  unfolded  states,  ∆G  = GFolded-GUnfolded  [45],  or  by  calculating  the  melting temperature, Tm. When the unfolding process is irreversible, the  system is not in thermodynamic equilibrium, and Tm  cannot be accu- rately calculated [45–47]. Here, the apparent melting temperature, Tm*,  is reported (Table 1). CD measurements at 208 and 291 nm yielded Tm*  values of 50.5  C and  ◦ C, with 125 μM, respectively. At both concentrations, the measured  52  ◦ C lower than those measured at 291 nm, which  Tm* at 208 nm was ~4  may indicate that the secondary structure is disturbed first, followed by  loss of tertiary structure. Similar phenomena of loss of tertiary structure  after  the  loss  of  secondary  structure  have  been  observed  in  thermal  denaturation  studies  of  other  proteins  [45,47].  Together,  the  results  provide the first insights into conditions that promote TcmN stability,  and the highest stability was achieved in 20 mM sodium phosphate pH 7,  100 mM NaI. Understanding and avoiding protein aggregation is another critical  aspect  of  enzyme  use  in  biotechnological  processes.  Transient  self-  interactions may explain the concentration dependence  on TcmN sta- bility since higher concentrations increase the probability of interaction,  facilitating  unfolding  and  aggregation  [48,49].  To  better  characterize  TcmN's concentration-dependent aggregation propensity, the possibility  of self-interaction was evaluated. Fig. 3 shows the 1H-15N HSQC NMR  spectrum of the free 15N-labeled TcmN (black) overlaid with the 15N-  labeled TcmN in the presence of 140 μM of unlabeled TcmN (red). Small  but consistent chemical shift variations were seen (Fig. 3), suggestive of  a transient interaction [50,51]. The CSP analysis revealed a broad dis- tribution of residues on the TcmN surface; however, residues showing  higher CSP values (Fig. 3) were more concentrated on one face of TcmN  (Fig.  3).  One  can  conjecture  that  in  a  condition  of  high  protein  con- centration,  self-interaction  could  play  a  role  in  TcmN  aggregation,  mainly when weak interactions occur between TcmN in an aggregation-  prone conformation, where hydrophobic residues are more exposed.  3.3. TcmN dynamics by NMR

TcmN dynamics likely play an essential role in its activity and sta- bility.  15N  NMR  relaxation  experiments  were  performed  to  explore  residue-specific  dynamics  on  ps-ns  and  ms-ms  timescales.  The  R2/R1  ratio, and the order parameter, S2, are shown in Fig. S4. A rotational  correlation time, τC, of 9.3 ± 0.7 ns, was obtained from the R2/R1 ratio,  which agrees with a monomeric state for TcmN at a concentration of  (cid:0) 1) (Fig. 4) and the S2 (Fig. S4B) were calculated from  180 μM. Aiming to build an atomistic picture of TcmN conformational equi- librium,  6  × 1  μs  MD  simulations  of  apo  TcmN  were  performed  and  analyzed.  Cα  RMSF  values  showed  high  flexibility  at  L5,  L7,  and  L9  (Fig.  5),  and  were  consistent  with  NMR  relaxation  measurements  (Fig. S4 and Fig. 4). PCA was used to identify dominant motions from the  MD trajectories. The first two components, PC1, and PC2, represented

Valadares et al.                                                                                                                                                                                                                            28 and 18% of the Cα conformational variance, respectively (Fig. S5A).  PC1 correlated strongly with L5-L9 distance (r2 = 0.82) (Fig. S5B). The  PC1-PC2 probability-based Gibbs free-energy landscape shows that the  first and second most populated regions correspond to closed and open  conformations, respectively (Fig. 6). Time traces of PC1 and PC2 evo- lution illustrates that the two minima were sampled by multiple replicas  (Fig. S6). Residues comprising the L3, L5, L7, and L9 loops, located at the  entrance  of  the  central  cavity,  were  major  contributors  to  conforma- tional  variance  of  the  PC1  and  PC2  modes  (Fig.  6).  Cavity  opening/  closing motions were well-separated along PC1, with an estimated en- ergy difference of ~3 kJ/mol between the closed and open states, and ~  6  kJ/mol  transition  free  energy.  The  free  energy  difference  between  states  is  an  approximate  estimate,  rather  than  a  rigorous  free  energy  calculation,  though  the  value  is  in  line with  a  spontaneous  transition  between  states  at  room  temperature,  as  well  as  the  experimentally  determined free energy of transition of a structurally similar protein, Fag  s 1 [11]. Cavity volumes were calculated from conformers of the two  principal energy basins. The average cavity volumes of the closed and  open states were 1211 ± 196 Å3 and 1713 ± 132 Å3 (t-test p < 0.0001),  respectively.

To check whether cavity opening leads to a conformation more prone  to aggregation, the aggregation propensity of representative conforma- tions  of  the  closed  and  the  opened  states  was  estimated  using  the  Aggrescan3D  (A3D)  server  [41],  which  utilizes  an  experimentally  derived intrinsic aggregation propensity value for natural amino acids,  and  projects  the  scale  onto  the  protein  structure,  considering  the  solvent-exposed surface area [41]. The open state showed more residues  with positive A3D values than the closed state, indicating that it may be  more susceptible to aggregation (Fig. 6-E). The A3D prediction shows  that  L5  and  L9  protect  the  hydrophobic  residues  in  the  cavity  in  the  closed  conformation.  However,  the  motions  of  L5  and  L9  transiently  expose  the  aggregation-prone  regions  to  the  solvent,  which  might  trigger aggregation. Although the open state of TcmN appears to be at  risk of aggregation, MD indicates that it is less prevalent than the closed  state (Fig. 6).

Movements of L5 and L9 could be necessary to allow the internali- zation of a linear polyketide chain into the cavity. The PC1 projection of  each frame and the distance between loops L5 and L9 (Fig. 7) showed  bimodal distributions and were analyzed with two Gaussian curves to  find the center of each peak. Two populations were observed with L5-L9  distances of 22.8 Å and 12.6 Å, corresponding to open and closed states,  respectively (Table S1). In the TcmN crystallographic structure (PDB ID:  2RER)  [4],  the  distance  between  L5-L9  is  9.1  Å,  corresponding  to  a  closed  conformation.  Changes  in  cavity  hydration  were  assessed  by  measuring the water content inside the cavity over the trajectories. A  strong correlation (r2 = 0.61) was obtained between the L5-L9 distance  and the number of water molecules inside the cavity (Fig. 7). The his- tograms revealed two clusters: one related to the closed state with an L5-  L9  distance  of  12.6  Å  and  ~  28  water  molecules,  and  another  corre- sponding to the open state, with an L5-L9 distance of 22.8 Å and ~ 36  water molecules (Table S1). The higher number of water molecules in- side the cavity in the open conformation may impose an entropic penalty  on this state by decreasing the solvent entropy, as the cavity is lined with  hydrophobic residues, which could contribute to the higher free energy  of the open state.

A  hydration  tuning  mechanism might  have  evolved  to control  the  opening  and  closing  of  Bet  v  1-like  proteins.  Like  TcmN,  the  higher-  energy, open state of Fag s 1 is entropically unfavorable due to the hy- drophobic  cavity's  exposure  to  solvent  [11,14].  It  is  likely  that  this  entropic penalty pressure TcmN and Fag s 1 to return to lower energy,  closed states. Similar results were observed by Oroguchi and Nakasako  [52], who investigated the modulation of the relative dynamics between  two domains of glutamate dehydrogenase by changes of local hydration  in the hydrophobic cleft between the two domains. They formulated a  model where the wetting/drying of a hydrophobic pocket worked as a  switch  for  interdomain  motions  [52].  Functional  protein  movements  might be coupled with changes in hydration structure [52,53]. Thus, it  may be possible to modulate the conformational equilibrium of Bet v 1-  like  proteins  by  changing  the  polar  and  apolar  residue  distributions  within the main cavity.  3.5. The interplay of conformational equilibrium, function, and  aggregation

Proteins  are  dynamic  molecules  and  may  sample  conformational  states that are at risk of misfolding and aggregation. The trade-off be- tween function vs. aggregation leads to an evolutionary pressure that  creates competition between increased binding efficiency and reduced  protein  stability,  balancing  the  ability  to  populate  multiple  states  without creating an unacceptable propensity for aggregation [54–56].  Inspired  by  the  work  of  Ferrolino  et  al.  [54]  with  the  β-rich  cellular  retinoic acid-binding protein 1, a scheme for describing the fine-tuned  interplay  between  conformational  flexibility,  function,  and  aggrega- tion  was  proposed  (Fig.  8).  Using  PC1  as  a  reaction  coordinate,  and  plotting it as a function of Gibbs free energy, we built an energy land- scape profile of TcmN (Fig. 8). In the model, TcmN is in conformational  equilibrium between closed and open conformational ensembles, with a  preference for the former. The open state is needed for substrate binding  but, at the same time, is more prone to amorphous aggregate formation  (Fig. 8). In the case of TcmN, it seems plausible that evolution solved the  function vs. aggregation problem by controlling the population of the  open state, and kinetically modulating its lifetime.

This work aimed to characterize the relationship between function,  conformational diversity, and stability of TcmN, an enzyme involved in  polyketide  production,  with  promising  biotechnological  applications.  TcmN presented higher thermal stability at the low protein and higher  salt concentrations, especially NaI. Thermal denaturation was irrevers- ible, leading to the formation of amorphous but not amyloidogenic ag- gregates. NMR studies indicated that transient self-interaction occurred,  which  may  promote  aggregation  at  higher  protein  concentrations.  Analysis  of  conformational  dynamics  by  NMR  and  MD  simulations  showed high flexibility of L5, L7, and L9, regulating the opening and  closing of the catalytic cavity for substrate binding and product release.  Open states expose hydrophobic residues inside the catalytic cavity to  solvent and are more aggregation-prone than closed conformations. Our  findings  present  a  crucial step  for  understanding  TcmN  function,  and  provide  valuable  information  for  future  TcmN  engineering  and  biotechnological applications. The work paves the way for studies that  aim  to  achieve  better  kinetic  control  of  TcmN,  and  reduce  its  self-  aggregation  by  guiding  structure-based  mutagenesis  of  loop  regions,  and aggregation-prone residues.
